    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1957-12-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1957-12-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="317"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d317">
                <head>317. Letter From the <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                    President’s Special Assistant (<persName corresp="#p_SHE1" type="to"
                        >Stassen</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d317fn1">Source:
                        Department of State, Central Files, 600.0012/12–2457. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1957-12-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 24, 1957</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear <persName corresp="#p_SHE1">Harold</persName>
                    </hi>: I have your memorandum of December 23.<note n="2" xml:id="d317fn2">
                        <ref target="#d316">
                            <hi rend="italic">Supra</hi>
                        </ref>.</note> I am sorry that the matter of your May 31 memorandum to
                        <persName corresp="#p_ZVA1">Zorin</persName> came up at my background press
                    conference. What I said, however, could have been no surprise to you. You will
                    recall that I cabled you on June 4, “I feel your memorandum to Soviet Delegation
                    of May 31 exceeded your authority both as to substance and procedure”;<note
                        n="3" xml:id="d317fn3">See <ref target="#d222">Document 222</ref>.</note>
                    and later the same day I sent you, with the personal approval of the President,
                    the instruction <pb facs="0810" n="782" xml:id="pg_782"/> to “notify Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_ZVA1">Zorin</persName> at the earliest possible moment
                    that the memorandum you submitted to him was not only informal and unofficial,
                    but had no approval in its submitted form either by the President or the State
                    Department, and that there are some aspects of the memorandum to which this
                    government cannot agree at this moment. Therefore you will request that Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_ZVA1">Zorin</persName> return the memorandum”.<note
                        n="4" xml:id="d317fn4">See <ref target="#d223">Document 223</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Under these circumstances, I could hardly have answered affirmatively the
                    question of “whether this memorandum was representative of the views of the
                    American Government”.</p>
                <p>I might say that the view that your memorandum exceeded your authority both as to
                    substance and procedure was concurred in at the time by both the Department of
                    Defense and the Atomic Energy Commission.</p>
                <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="strong">John Foster Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="5" xml:id="d317fn5">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
